  <title>Description</title>
  <titlealts>
    <searchtitle>NHS Business Definition: Sentinel Lymph Node - Description</searchtitle>
  </titlealts>
  <body>
  <div>
    <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_sentinel_lymph_node">Sentinel Lymph Node</xref>
 is a 
              <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_cell_pathological_abnormality">CELL PATHOLOGICAL ABNORMALITY</xref>.        </p>
    <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_sentinel_lymph_node">Sentinel Lymph Node</xref>
 is the first 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_lymph_node">Lymph Node</xref>
 to which cancer is likely to spread from the primary 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_tumour">Tumour</xref>. When cancer spreads, the cancer 
              <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_cell">CELLS</xref>
 may appear first in the 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_sentinel_lymph_node">Sentinel Lymph Node</xref>
 before spreading to other 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_lymph_node">Lymph Nodes</xref>.        </p>
    <p>
For further information on 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_sentinel_lymph_node">Sentinel Lymph Nodes</xref>, see the 
              <xref href="https://www.cancer.gov/dictionary?CdrID=45876" scope="external" format="html">National Cancer Institute website</xref>.        </p>
  </div>
